<P>
SACRAMENTO; 
</P>
<P>
DOG DAYS TOUGH ON CARRIAGE HORSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mayor Anne Rudin and other city officials are looking for ways to protect 
carriage horses in historic Old Sacramento from the horrors of 100-degree heat. 
Mike Winters of the Sacramento Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals 
said the city should give horses a four-hour work day, ban carriage-pulling 
between noon and 7 p.m. when the temperature rises above 80, and limit 
carriages to no more than four passengers. 
</P>
